<div class="timeline">
  <div class="timeline-item">
    <span class="timeline-date">2022</span>
    <div class="timeline-card">
      <h3 data-cms-field="weg_1_h3">The Discipline Begins</h3>
      <p data-cms-field="weg_1_p">I started taking the gym seriously. Not just showing up — really training. Bulking phases, shredding phases, pushing heavier, pulling harder, always chasing the next challenge. For the first time, I felt what consistency could do to both body and mind.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="timeline-item">
    <span class="timeline-date">2023</span>
    <div class="timeline-card">
      <h3 data-cms-field="weg_2_h3">Running for Something Bigger</h3>
      <p data-cms-field="weg_2_p">I kept building my discipline in the gym, but something was missing — water. I went back to swimming once a week, reconnecting with a sport that had always been part of me. Then my coach suggested something unexpected: a half-marathon. I had never run one before, but the idea stuck. For six months I followed a structured plan — running three times a week and lifting twice — through the dark, cold German winter.</p>
      <p data-cms-field="weg_2_p2">My mom was battling leukemia that year. In April, I ran my very first half-marathon in her honor. She was already very tired. She passed away in November.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="timeline-item">
    <span class="timeline-date">2024</span>
    <div class="timeline-card">
      <h3 data-cms-field="weg_3_h3">The Leap into Triathlon</h3>
      <p data-cms-field="weg_3_p">Losing my mom changed how I see time. It pushed me to stop waiting. I had been thinking about triathlon for a while — and in 2024 I finally jumped in. Training suddenly had three disciplines, three rhythms, three new ways to grow. Actually, four — gym has always been there.</p>
      <p data-cms-field="weg_3_p2">In September, I stood on the start line of my first race: the Hannover Sprint Triathlon. 12th in my age group — 1:24:10.</p>
      <p class="timeline-quote" data-cms-field="weg_3_quote">"It was insanely fantastic. A milestone. I wanted more."</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="timeline-item">
    <span class="timeline-date">2025</span>
    <div class="timeline-card">
      <h3 data-cms-field="weg_4_h3">The Fire Gets Real</h3>
      <p data-cms-field="weg_4_p">Triathlon stopped being just a passion and became my highest priority. Training gave structure to a year still shaped by grief — something solid to hold on to.</p>
      <p data-cms-field="weg_4_p2">May: 5150 Kraichgau, 6th AG, 2:52:57. I always cry at the finish line. July: WTCS Hamburg, 7th AG, 2:36:49. My jump at the finish line replaced any caption: unstoppable! September: 70.3 Ironman Cervia, 35°C, dehydration from km 50. Quitting crossed my mind but was never an option. 9th AG, 5:42:36.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="timeline-item timeline-highlight">
    <span class="timeline-date">2026</span>
    <div class="timeline-card">
      <h3 data-cms-field="weg_5_h3">The Road to Nice</h3>
      <p data-cms-field="weg_5_p">April: 70.3 Brasilia — qualification race. Back in my country, close to family. Then: Ironman World Championship Nice. Every session, every race, every early morning leads in that direction.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
